			<h1>Extending a Hand</h1>
			<p>There are numerous ways individuals and communities can extend a helping hand to US veterans, ensuring they receive the support and gratitude they deserve for their service. 
			One impactful approach is to contribute to reputable veteran- focused charities and organizations that provide a wide range of services. 
			Donations to well-established nonprofits like the Wounded Warrior Project or Homes for Our Troops can make a significant difference in the lives of veterans in need. 
			Whether it's through financial contributions, volunteering, or advocacy, each act of support contributes to a collective effort to give back to those who have sacrificed so much for our country.
			</p>
			<p>
			Supporting US veterans is essential to express gratitude for their service and help them transition to civilian life. Here are some ways you can support a US veteran:
			</p>
			<ul>
				<li><strong>Volunteer:</strong> Offer your time and skills to veteran-focused organizations such as those noted above.</li>
				<li><strong>Donate:</strong> Contribute to veteran-related charities or nonprofits that provide essential services and support to veterans and their families.</li>
				<li><strong>Mentorship:</strong> Offer mentorship or career advice to veterans who are transitioning to civilian life, helping them find suitable job opportunities or educational paths.</li>
				<li><strong>Employment Assistance:</strong> If you are an employer or know someone who is, consider hiring veterans and providing them with job opportunities.</li>
				<li><strong>Advocate for Veteran Rights:</strong> Advocate for policies that benefit veterans, including improved healthcare, mental health services, and access to educational opportunities.</li>
				<li><strong>Support PTSD Awareness:</strong> Raise awareness about post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) and its effects on veterans' lives. Encourage those who may be struggling to seek help.</li>
			</ul>
			<h2>Wounded Warrior</h2>
			<img src='https://www.woundedwarriorproject.org/media/ugbk5cf1/wwp21_brand_wban_wwpweb_180x150px_v2.jpg' alt='Wounded Warrior Project' height="300"/>
			<p><a href="https://www.woundedwarriorproject.org">The Wounded Warrior Project</a> is a nonprofit organization that provides a range of programs and services to support injured veterans and their families, assisting them in their transition to civilian life. 
			They focus on offering mental and physical health support, career counseling, and social engagement opportunities to improve the lives of wounded veterans (Wounded Warrior Project, n.d.).
			</p>
			<h2>Operation Phone Home</h2>
			<img src="images/phone.jpg" alt="Soldier holding a phone" height="300">
			<p><a href="https://www.uso.org/programs/operation-phone-home">Operation Phone Home</a> is an initiative that aims to provide US military veterans with free international calls, connecting them with their loved ones stationed overseas or in distant locations. 
			The program helps foster communication and support for veterans and their families during times of separation (Operation Phone Home, n.d.).
			</p>
			<h2>Homes for Our Troops</h2>
			<img src="images/homes.jpg" alt="Homes For Our Troops logo" height="300">
			<p><a href="https://www.hfotusa.org">Homes for Our Troops</a> is a nonprofit organization that constructs specially adapted homes for severely injured post-9/11 veterans, enabling them to regain their independence and improve their quality of life. 
			Through their efforts, they provide mortgage-free homes that are designed to accommodate the unique needs and challenges faced by these veterans (Homes For Our Troops, n.d.).
			</p>
			<h2>Veterans Honor Flight</h2>
			<img src="images/flight.jpg" alt="Veterans Honor Flight logo" height="300">
			<p><a href="https://www.honorflight.org">Veterans Honor Flight</a> is a nonprofit organization that arranges all-expenses-paid trips for military veterans to visit and reflect at the memorials in Washington, D.C. 
			The program aims to honor and express gratitude to veterans for their service and sacrifices (Veterans Honor Flight, n.d.).
			</p>
